trichotillomania for people that suffer from it how did your family take it when you told them that you had it how did you explain to them what it was i don't necessarily suffer from it it's just a part of my life my family wanted to know if there was anything i could do about it my mom said what most people say just stop doing it which i find to be just plain ignorant and stupid my sister had known for a long time and she doesn't really have any problem with it or anything i explained it as a type of obsessive compulsive disorder that causes me to pull my hair out and the hair pulling makes me feel relieved or calmed when i do it i told them it's a relatively newly studied disorder and not many doctors or psychiatrists know what to do about it or how to treat it i told them that at this point in my life i'm not too concerned about it or really willing to give it up my mother in law has been extremely understanding and bought me special makeup for my wedding so that i could realistically make my eyebrows look fuller i don't have any bald patches so it doesn't really affect anyone else on a regular basis but it is a part of my life and the hair pulling is usually a part of my daily routine Trichotillomania Obsessive-compulsive disorder Baldness Kodocha Anxiety Prostate cancer Bipolar disorder Non-Hodgkin's lymphoma Autism Hair Asperger syndrome Mental illness Theory of conduct Stomach cancer Eating disorder Addiction Transactional analysis Hormone replacement therapy (trans) Narcissism Friends Dilbert Chronic fatigue syndrome Charmed Post-traumatic stress disorder EastEnders Shaggy dog story Procrastination Anti-psychiatry Borderline personality disorder Fathers' rights Little Britain Psychiatry Psychology Serial killer Alopecia areata Psychotherapy Clinical depression Adult attention-deficit disorder Days of our Lives Dissociative identity disorder Psychiatric hospital Psychosis Cognitive therapy Antisocial personality disorder Similarities between the Bible and the